d) it, and it's ridiculous that someone has actually been there 15 days straight - but this person obviously feels it worthwhile.  Once the people that DON'T feel it worth the long camp get it, then it'll turn back into a &quot;dropin&quot; camp again.<br><br>  <p>Morkenlar<BR>Infinitus Vindicat</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uismena.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ismena</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/17/01 8:11:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus95980frm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=150.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Zordak Ragefire on Rotation? (A Pro/Con Discussion)</span><hr size=1> Well, I thought no one had been fooled by Jaharad's post, till I saw this one.  Seliah, yours is a very reasonable post, and I hope we can use it as a springboard to initiate some reasonable discussion about this problem, but I need to answer a couple of things you said in your first paragraph, concerning a list:<br><br>The brouhaha was started when someone I had considered a &quot;friend&quot; for well over a year hailed me from Ajahn's account.  He became abusive and began screaming at me for having the gall to let a family member sit at my computer while I got four hours' sleep on the -- what was it, the eighth day of my camp?  He insisted that I had violated the rules of the camp and forfeited my place in line.  (Pretty funny, isn't it, when he's hailing me from Ajahn's account?)  He called me a liar when I said I was now the person at the keyboard, called me a liar again when I said it would be me for the rest of the day, accused me of having been offline for six hours (the number later became four, then two, but was in any case patently absurd) and called me a liar when I denied it, called me a liar when I said I had been in line for eight days (his only evidence having been that he didn't believe such a thing was possible), claimed a cleric of &quot;his&quot; had been kept from camping Zordak, then claimed the same cleric had come to Sol B and checked to see if I was there and found I wasn't (another bald-faced lie), then switched to his own account to attack me further.  He insisted I had given up my place in line and that he and IV would FFA the spawn (thus ignoring the other three clerics also doing butt time down there).<br><br>After I put him on /ignore he came to Sol B and started /shouting at me (I wasn't aware of all the noise till I started getting /tells, &quot;Can you believe this guy?&quot;) and at everyone else in the zone that I was a liar and a cheat and had violated the rules when I logged off for hours at a time.  Everyone in the zone, most of whom were very tired of hearing me answer virtually every camp check (I may have missed one or two while we were clearing FG's) told him he was wrong.  Not even that stopped him, but he continued his tirade of /shouts.<br><br>I took him off ignore when I learned what was going on.  He filled my chatscreen with purple.  I soon began to realise that his real obsession was that he believed my guild and some other &quot;Uberguilds&quot; (IV is not uber?) were conspiring to keep people from getting in line to camp Zordak.  (One wonders how the heck we could have done that?)<br><br>Actually, the real problem started when a monk from Stasis, whose User was seriously ill and on an extended leave from work, camped in SolB and started helping the clerics clear fire giants.  I guess that meant that we were controlling something.  True, Tremmor had some names, and true, now and then he would hail someone and tell them, &quot;Zordak just died, the line is down to two, come get in line.&quot;  Not all the clerics were from big guilds; in fact several other clerics had got in the line never even having heard of the so-called list.  Then one very upset person hailed Tremmor and started ... well, I wasn't in on the exchange, so no comment about it here ... so he told her her cleric was twelfth on the list.  There never was a list with twelve names on it, but some people just can't help themselves when Maddie starts trying to bully them; they get a bit of a kick in provoking him.  (/apologise Maddie)  In reality, the collection of names started with eight and dwindled from there.<br><br>There never was an enforceable list; how could there have been?  There was a line, mutually enforced by the clerics in it.  I invited Jaharad to have &quot;his&quot; cleric come get in line, but he didn't want to be reasonable; he continued to insist we were keeping people off the list.  (Note that he never learned the difference between a &quot;list&quot; and a &quot;line&quot;.)  He also changed his story and insisted he didn't have a cleric, nor did he have anything to gain.  But he continued to batter me with accusations of controlling the list and keeping his cleric out of it.  (For God's sake, the IV cleric who is most ready for Ragefire just happens to be a dear friend of mine, Darkhealer, whom I would love to see epicified!)<br><br>Finally, he took his log of our exchange, HEAVILY edited it, and publicly posted it on the General Discussion here at prexus.com.  I had given him permission to post the log in its entirety including the screaming and accusations from Ajahn's account, but he omitted those.  He seemed to think that his case needed strengthening, so he took out many of the more neurotic things he said (you can tell when reading my replies that they are replies to something he said, but what he said appears nowhere), added a number of personal insults (he called me fat LOL), and posted it.<br><br>Somehow Jaharad seems to have expected that post to have brought the ridicule of the community down on my head, but it backfired on him.  People with a brain (that's most but not all of the people on Prexus) were able to figure out that an electronic image with no substance would be unable to keep another insubstantial image from going where it chose, given a little time.  No, we didn't park a troll at the entrance to keep the halflings from getting by and getting in line.  No, we didn't have the keys to either the front door or the back doors of Sol B.  No, &quot;we&quot; never ignored someone who had spent twelve days clearing fire giants with us, only to FFA his Zordak just because he had never heard of the list.  But Jaharad seems to think we did.<br><br>The emotional upset this event caused me I'm reluctant to describe.  Cidwin did a good job of it when he posted his reply.  Let me just say I cried, I lost sleep, and I had nightmares.  I'm still waiting to hear one word of retraction from Jah or his guild leader, or anyone in IV, other than Darkhealer, who remains my friend.  Yes, Jaharad sent me one /tell: &quot;congratulations&quot;, to which I answered, &quot;thank you.&quot;  I guess that's all I'm worth.<br><br>Perhaps you should also know that a few days before that, I was hailed by a cleric who confided to me that she didn't have time to sit the miserably long camp, and that her only hope would be to get ingame first after the next patch to claim the front place in line.<br><br>This is the result of not having a rotation.  I feel very bitter toward the people who oppose it.  And I want to thank Seliah for the pleasant, intelligent post. <p><img src=http://people.we.mediaone.net/hwaet/Ismena.jpg><BR>Ismena, 58 Barbiedoll Cleric<BR>Fieniel, 34 darling Drood<BR>Alethea, 26 Barbiedoll Bard<BR>Connye, 18 Semia-faced Monk<BR>Prexus</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uismena.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ismena</A> at: 8/17/01 8:28:20 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/umorkenlar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Morken